            <div class="metric-row">
                <div class="metric-item">
                    <div class="metric-header">
                        <div>
                            <div class="metric-label">
                                PCE Inflation (Personal Consumption Expenditures)
                                <span class="tooltip">
                                    <span class="info-icon">‚ÑπÔ∏è</span>
                                    <span class="tooltiptext">
                                        <strong>What it is:</strong> The Fed's preferred inflation measure tracking price changes in consumer goods and services.<br><br>
                                        <strong>Why it matters:</strong> Unlike CPI, PCE accounts for substitution (when people switch to cheaper alternatives). Fed targets 2% PCE inflation.<br><br>
                                        <strong>Current reading:</strong> 2.7% (October forecast) shows sticky inflation, higher than August's 2.7%.
                                    </span>
                                </span>
                            </div>
                            <div class="metric-value flow-neutral">2.7%</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="metric-change up">‚ñ≤ Forecast</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="metric-explanation">
                        <strong>Oct 2025 (Forecast):</strong> Inflation remains sticky at 2.7%. Official data delayed by government shutdown. Fed watching closely as inflation not declining as hoped.
                    </div>
                    <div class="data-source">Source: Bureau of Economic Analysis (BEA)</div>
                </div>

                <div class="metric-item">
                    <div class="metric-header">
                        <div>
                            <div class="metric-label">
                                Core PCE (Excluding Food & Energy)
                                <span class="tooltip">
                                    <span class="info-icon">‚ÑπÔ∏è</span>
                                    <span class="tooltiptext">
                                        <strong>What it is:</strong> PCE inflation minus volatile food and energy prices.<br><br>
                                        <strong>Why it matters:</strong> Shows underlying inflation trends without noise from gas and grocery swings. Fed watches this closely for policy decisions.<br><br>
                                        <strong>Current reading:</strong> 2.7% (October forecast), improved from 2.9% in August but still above 2% target.
                                    </span>
                                </span>
                            </div>
                            <div class="metric-value flow-neutral">2.7%</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="metric-change down">‚ñº From 2.9%</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="metric-explanation">
                        <strong>Oct 2025 (Forecast):</strong> Improvement from August's 2.9% to 2.7%. Progress toward target but still elevated. Services inflation remains sticky component.
                    </div>
                    <div class="data-source">Source: Bureau of Economic Analysis (BEA)</div>
                </div>

                <div class="metric-item">
                    <div class="metric-header">
                        <div>
                            <div class="metric-label">
                                CPI (Consumer Price Index)
                                <span class="tooltip">
                                    <span class="info-icon">‚ÑπÔ∏è</span>
                                    <span class="tooltiptext">
                                        <strong>What it is:</strong> Measures average price changes for a basket of consumer goods and services.<br><br>
                                        <strong>Why it matters:</strong> Most widely reported inflation metric. Affects cost-of-living adjustments for Social Security. Higher than PCE due to methodology differences.<br><br>
                                        <strong>Current reading:</strong> 3.0% (September 2025) shows reacceleration from prior months.
                                    </span>
                                </span>
                            </div>
                            <div class="metric-value flow-caution">3.0%</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="metric-change up">‚ñ≤ 0.3% MoM</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="metric-explanation">
                        <strong>Sept 2025:</strong> Inflation reaccelerated to 3.0%. Shelter costs remain stubbornly elevated. October data delayed indefinitely due to government shutdown.
                    </div>
                    <div class="data-source">Source: Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS)</div>
                </div>

                <div class="metric-item">
                    <div class="metric-header">
                        <div>
                            <div class="metric-label">
                                GDP Growth (Real, Annualized Q2 2025)
                                <span class="tooltip">
                                    <span class="info-icon">‚ÑπÔ∏è</span>
                                    <span class="tooltiptext">
                                        <strong>What it is:</strong> Real Gross Domestic Product measures total economic output adjusted for inflation, annualized.<br><br>
                                        <strong>Why it matters:</strong> Key indicator of economic health. 2-3% growth considered healthy. Below 0% is recession. Affects corporate earnings expectations.<br><br>
                                        <strong>Current reading:</strong> 3.8% shows robust rebound after Q1 contraction (-0.6%). Strong consumer spending.
                                    </span>
                                </span>
                            </div>
                            <div class="metric-value flow-positive">3.8%</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="metric-change up">‚ñ≤ from -0.6% Q1</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="metric-explanation">
                        <strong>Q2 2025:</strong> Strong 3.8% growth driven by consumer spending and decreased imports. Sharp recovery from Q1's -0.6% contraction. Economy showing resilience.
                    </div>
                    <div class="data-source">Source: Bureau of Economic Analysis (BEA)</div>
                </div>

                <div class="metric-item">
                    <div class="metric-header">
                        <div>
                            <div class="metric-label">
                                Unemployment Rate
                                <span class="tooltip">
                                    <span class="info-icon">‚ÑπÔ∏è</span>
                                    <span class="tooltiptext">
                                        <strong>What it is:</strong> Percentage of labor force actively seeking work but unemployed.<br><br>
                                        <strong>Why it matters:</strong> Low unemployment = tight labor market = wage pressure = inflation risk. Fed watches for "maximum employment" mandate (3.5-4.5% range is healthy).<br><br>
                                        <strong>Current reading:</strong> 4.3% (August 2025) slightly above ideal, shows modest labor market cooling.
                                    </span>
                                </span>
                            </div>
                            <div class="metric-value flow-neutral">4.3%</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="metric-change up">‚ñ≤ Slight increase</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="metric-explanation">
                        <strong>Aug 2025:</strong> Modest rise to 4.3%. Payrolls added just 22K jobs. Labor market cooling but not collapsing. September report delayed due to shutdown.
                    </div>
                    <div class="data-source">Source: Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS)</div>
                </div>

                <div class="metric-item">
                    <div class="metric-header">
                        <div>
                            <div class="metric-label">
                                NFCI (National Financial Conditions Index)
                                <span class="tooltip">
                                    <span class="info-icon">‚ÑπÔ∏è</span>
                                    <span class="tooltiptext">
                                        <strong>What it is:</strong> Chicago Fed's index tracking 105 indicators of financial stress (credit spreads, volatility, funding costs).<br><br>
                                        <strong>Why it matters:</strong> Negative = loose financial conditions = easy credit = bullish for risk assets. Positive = tight conditions = stress = bearish.<br><br>
                                        <strong>Current reading:</strong> -0.53 (week ending Nov 7, 2025) shows even looser financial conditions than before.
                                    </span>
                                </span>
                            </div>
                            <div class="metric-value flow-positive">-0.53</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="metric-change">Very Loose</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="metric-explanation">
                        <strong>Nov 7, 2025:</strong> Extremely accommodative at -0.53, unchanged from prior week. Risk (-0.27), credit (-0.16), leverage (-0.10) all loose. Highly bullish for stocks.
                    </div>
                    <div class="data-source">Source: Chicago Fed</div>
                </div>

                <div class="metric-item">
                    <div class="metric-header">
                        <div>
                            <div class="metric-label">
                                Fed Funds Rate
                                <span class="tooltip">
                                    <span class="info-icon">‚ÑπÔ∏è</span>
                                    <span class="tooltiptext">
                                        <strong>What it is:</strong> The interest rate at which banks lend to each other overnight. Set by Federal Reserve.<br><br>
                                        <strong>Why it matters:</strong> Most important rate in economy. Affects mortgages, corporate borrowing, savings rates. Fed uses it to control inflation and employment.<br><br>
                                        <strong>Current reading:</strong> 3.75-4.0% after October 30, 2025 cut. Fed easing cycle underway with 75bps of cuts in 2025.
                                    </span>
                                </span>
                            </div>
                            <div class="metric-value">3.75-4.0%</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="metric-change down">‚ñº Cut 0.25% Oct 30</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="metric-explanation">
                        <strong>Oct 30, 2025:</strong> Fed cut 25bps to 3.75-4.0% range. Continued easing despite sticky 3% inflation. Balancing growth support vs inflation concerns.
                    </div>
                    <div class="data-source">Source: Federal Reserve</div>
                </div>

                <div class="metric-item">
                    <div class="metric-header">
                        <div>
                            <div class="metric-label">
                                Real Wage Growth
                                <span class="tooltip">
                                    <span class="info-icon">‚ÑπÔ∏è</span>
                                    <span class="tooltiptext">
                                        <strong>What it is:</strong> Nominal wage growth minus inflation = actual purchasing power gains.<br><br>
                                        <strong>Why it matters:</strong> Positive real wage growth = consumers can buy more = supports consumer spending (70% of GDP). But too high = inflation pressure.<br><br>
                                        <strong>Current reading:</strong> Positive for most workers as wages outpace 3.0% inflation, supporting consumption.
                                    </span>
                                </span>
                            </div>
                            <div class="metric-value flow-positive">Positive</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="metric-change up">‚ñ≤ Above inflation</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="metric-explanation">
                        <strong>2025:</strong> Wages still outpacing 3% inflation for most workers. Supports strong consumer spending seen in Q2 GDP. Fed watching wage-price dynamics closely.
                    </div>
                    <div class="data-source">Source: BLS, Fed Analysis</div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="info-box" style="background: rgba(102, 126, 234, 0.15); border-color: #667eea;">
                <h3>üìñ How to Read These Indicators</h3>
                <p>
                    <strong>Inflation metrics (PCE, Core PCE, CPI):</strong> Closer to 2% = better for stocks. Above 3% = Fed may raise rates = bearish.<br>
                    <strong>GDP:</strong> 2-3% = goldilocks. Above 4% = overheating risk. Below 1% = recession concerns.<br>
                    <strong>Unemployment:</strong> 3.5-4.5% = healthy. Above 5% = weakness. Below 3% = inflation risk.<br>
                    <strong>NFCI:</strong> Negative = good for risk assets. Positive = tightening conditions = defensive.<br>
                    <strong>Fed Funds:</strong> Higher = more expensive borrowing = bearish. Lower = stimulative = bullish.
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>

