                <!-- Explanation -->
                <div style="background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3); padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; margin-bottom: 20px;">
                    <h4 style="color: #ef4444; margin-bottom: 15px; font-size: 1.1rem;">üìñ What is a Flow Reversal?</h4>
                    <p style="color: #d0d0e8; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 15px;">
                        A <strong>flow reversal</strong> occurs when the TIC (Treasury International Capital) data turns negative for 2 or more consecutive months. This means foreign investors are <strong>net sellers</strong> of US securities (stocks, bonds, treasuries) rather than buyers.
                    </p>

                    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin-top: 20px;">
                        <div>
                            <h5 style="color: #667eea; margin-bottom: 10px;">üî¥ Why 2+ Months is Critical:</h5>
                            <ul style="color: #d0d0e8; font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.6; padding-left: 20px;">
                                <li><strong>One month</strong> = Could be noise, rebalancing, or temporary</li>
                                <li><strong>Two months</strong> = Suggests a trend change in sentiment</li>
                                <li><strong>Three+ months</strong> = Confirmed capital flight pattern</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>

                        <div>
                            <h5 style="color: #667eea; margin-bottom: 10px;">‚ö° What It Signals:</h5>
                            <ul style="color: #d0d0e8; font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.6; padding-left: 20px;">
                                <li>Loss of confidence in US assets</li>
                                <li>Potential USD weakness (less foreign demand)</li>
                                <li>Higher bond yields needed to attract capital</li>
                                <li>Equity market vulnerable to correction</li>
                                <li>Often precedes recession or crisis</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Historical Context -->
                <div style="background: rgba(245, 158, 11, 0.1); padding: 20px; border-radius: 10px; border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b; margin-bottom: 20px;">
                    <h4 style="color: #f59e0b; margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 1rem;">üìä Historical Examples of Flow Reversals:</h4>
                    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); gap: 15px;">
                        <div style="background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2); padding: 12px; border-radius: 5px;">
                            <div style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: #f59e0b; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 5px;">2008 Financial Crisis</div>
                            <div style="font-size: 0.8rem; color: #d0d0e8;">Sustained outflows Q3-Q4 2008. S&P 500 fell -38% from peak.</div>
                        </div>
                        <div style="background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2); padding: 12px; border-radius: 5px;">
                            <div style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: #f59e0b; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 5px;">COVID Crash (March 2020)</div>
                            <div style="font-size: 0.8rem; color: #d0d0e8;">Sharp but brief outflows. -34% SPX drop in 23 days.</div>
                        </div>
                        <div style="background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2); padding: 12px; border-radius: 5px;">
                            <div style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: #f59e0b; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 5px;">2022 Rate Hikes</div>
                            <div style="font-size: 0.8rem; color: #d0d0e8;">Intermittent outflows as Fed raised rates. Tech down -33%.</div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

